name: benzoylhydrazine, o-chloro
Reason: The basic unit of consideration here is benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5 degrees Celsius. The introduction of various functional groups alters this melting point. The amide group (C(=O)NH-) typically increases melting points significantly due to the potential for hydrogen bonding and the dipole associated with the carbonyl group; this can be estimated as a +80 increase. The hydrazine group (NH-NH2) linked to the carbonyl also significantly raises the melting point due to added N-H...N hydrogen bonding and potential for extended molecular interactions; this can add roughly +40. An ortho-substituted chlorine (Cl) on the benzene ring can increase the melting point by about +15, attributed to its electronegativity and slightly larger atomic size contributing to van der Waals forces. Cumulatively, the expected increase from all functional groups is approximately 80 + 40 + 15.
